 And this older home had this one room at the back of the house.

14
00:01:12,000 --> 00:01:17,000
 And that one room had its own air conditioning unit.

15
00:01:17,000 --> 00:01:20,000
 You're like, "Why are we talking about HVAC?" Well, let me tell you.

16
00:01:20,000 --> 00:01:27,000
 The previous owners had bought an air conditioning system for this one room

17
00:01:27,000 --> 00:01:32,000
 that was just too big for the room. And I don't know all the ins and outs of HVAC,

18
00:01:32,000 --> 00:01:39,000
 but what my friend told me was happening was that this system was short-cycling,

19
00:01:39,000 --> 00:01:44,000
 which means that it was overproducing.

20
00:01:44,000 --> 00:01:47,000
 So without my friends Sterling and Natalie knowing it,

21
00:01:47,000 --> 00:01:56,000
 there was moisture that was forming on the inside of the unit without them knowing,

22
00:01:56,000 --> 00:02:00,000
 and it was causing mold to build up in the unit.

23
00:02:00,000 --> 00:02:05,000
 The problem is that my friend Natalie has a condition where her body

24
00:02:05,000 --> 00:02:11,000
 struggles to eliminate toxins. She's had this struggle for about two decades.

25
00:02:11,000 --> 00:02:14,000
 And so I want you to think about what was happening.

26
00:02:14,000 --> 00:02:19,000
 Without them knowing it, this air conditioning unit was quietly operating

27
00:02:19,000 --> 00:02:22,000
 in the background of their lives every single day,

28
00:02:22,000 --> 00:02:25,000
 and it was blowing air through their home,

29
00:02:25,000 --> 00:02:32,000
 which was actually poisoning Natalie's body and sabotaging her health.

30
00:02:32,000 --> 00:02:40,000
 The reason I tell you that is because tonight we're going to talk about our past failures.

31
00:02:40,000 --> 00:02:45,000
 We're talking about that moment or that season in your past

32
00:02:45,000 --> 00:02:49,000
 that you could just slap the label on, "What was I thinking?"

33
00:02:49,000 --> 00:02:54,000
 For some of you, it was like college. It was like, "Well, what part of college?"

34
00:02:54,000 --> 00:03:01,000
 College. "What was I thinking?" Not going to it, but what you did in college.

35
00:03:01,000 --> 00:03:04,000
 Some of you all were like it was freshman year of college,

36
00:03:04,000 --> 00:03:08,000
 or for others it was like it was the relationship with that girl

37
00:03:08,000 --> 00:03:14,000
 or that guy or that choice I made in my first job or that abortion.

38
00:03:14,000 --> 00:03:21,000
 It was that choice in my past that when you look back on it,

39
00:03:21,000 --> 00:03:28,000
 it just causes shame, regret.

40
00:03:28,000 --> 00:03:33,000
 And without us realizing it, our past failures can be a lot like

41
00:03:33,000 --> 00:03:35,000
 my friend's air conditioning unit.

42
00:03:35,000 --> 00:03:40,000
 Our past failures can quietly operate in the background of our lives,

43
00:03:40,000 --> 00:03:44,000
 blowing shame and regret through our souls like air through a house.

44
00:03:44,000 --> 00:03:52,000
 And that shame and regret can poison our souls, and it can lead to all sorts of issues.

45
00:03:52,000 --> 00:03:56,000
 It'll impact your relationship with God. It'll impact your relationship with others.

46
00:03:56,000 --> 00:04:00,000
 It'll impact your future marriage and the way that you parent your kids.

47
00:04:00,000 --> 00:04:06,000
 Like, our shame and regret has to be dealt with.

48
00:04:06,000 --> 00:04:10,000
 And so I don't know what you think of when I ask you, "What is it?

49
00:04:10,000 --> 00:04:12,000
 What is it from your past?"

50
00:04:12,000 --> 00:04:15,000
 So when you look back on it, you just think, "What was I thinking?"

51
00:04:15,000 --> 00:04:20,000
 Like, if you could have a do-over, if you just could hit a button

52
00:04:20,000 --> 00:04:26,000
 that would cause things to loop back and you could just try it again

53
00:04:26,000 --> 00:04:29,000
 or do it differently, what would it be for you?

54
00:04:29,000 --> 00:04:33,000
 I just want you to know that this talk is deeply personal for me,

55
00:04:33,000 --> 00:04:38,000
 and I've shared my story here at the porch a lot, but if you're new here,

56
00:04:38,000 --> 00:04:43,000
 the reality is during my young adult years, I was here in Dallas.

57
00:04:43,000 --> 00:04:49,000
 I was going to Dallas Seminary like I was getting a degree in Jesus.

58
00:04:49,000 --> 00:04:53,000
 And at the same time, I was working at a church with high school students,

59
00:04:53,000 --> 00:04:58,000
 and I was telling high school students one way to live.

60
00:04:58,000 --> 00:05:05,000
 And then at the same time, in my private life, I was doing the opposite,

61
00:05:05,000 --> 00:05:08,000
 and I was living a compromising life.

62
00:05:08,000 --> 00:05:13,000
 I was making compromising decisions, and those compromising decisions

63
00:05:13,000 --> 00:05:16,000
 led to major consequences in my life.

64
00:05:16,000 --> 00:05:22,000
 It all boiled up to a point where I had to sit with about 50 or 60 staff members

65
00:05:22,000 --> 00:05:27,000
 at the church I was working at and share with them my sin.

66
00:05:27,000 --> 00:05:31,000
 And I had to step out of all forms of leadership in ministry.

67
00:05:31,000 --> 00:05:36,000
 And when that happened, man, shame and regret moved in

68
00:05:36,000 --> 00:05:42,000
 and made themselves at home, and my failures began to quietly operate

69
00:05:42,000 --> 00:05:49,000
 in the background of my life, and my past failure began to blow shame

70
00:05:49,000 --> 00:05:52,000
 and regret through the soul, through the house of my soul,

71
00:05:52,000 --> 00:05:55,000
 like air through my friend's house.

72
00:05:55,000 --> 00:06:00,000
 And it impacted me in so many ways, so many ways.

73
00:06:00,000 --> 00:06:06,000
 Like I remember going to that church, and whenever I would go to that church,

74
00:06:06,000 --> 00:06:09,000
 it was like everyone--I just thought everyone was looking at me

75
00:06:09,000 --> 00:06:13,000
 like I began to believe everyone saw me for my sin,

76
00:06:13,000 --> 00:06:17,000
 or if I saw someone out in public from that church, I just began to think,

77
00:06:17,000 --> 00:06:21,000
 "Well, they probably, when they see me, they just think about what I've done."

78
00:06:21,000 --> 00:06:27,000
 Or when I started dating my wife, Catherine, she just had a cleaner past than me.

79
00:06:27,000 --> 00:06:33,000
 And so I felt unworthy of God's good gift of Catherine in my life.

80
00:06:33,000 --> 00:06:35,000
 I just didn't believe that I deserved her.

81
00:06:35,000 --> 00:06:39,000
 Like I deserved something less because of my past.

82
00:06:39,000 --> 00:06:44,000
 Or when I got back into ministry and I became a student pastor,

83
00:06:44,000 --> 00:06:49,000
 I felt so ashamed to be in ministry with the past that I had

84
00:06:49,000 --> 00:06:55,000
 because I thought that I was unqualified.

85
00:06:55,000 --> 00:06:59,000
 Let me change that wording because we're all in some ways unqualified for ministry.

86
00:06:59,000 --> 00:07:06,000
 I felt unfit. I felt unusable by God.

87
00:07:06,000 --> 00:07:10,000
 And then I also operated with this mentality that I just wanted to get

88
00:07:10,000 --> 00:07:15,000
 as far away from my failure as quickly as possible

89
00:07:15,000 --> 00:07:20,000
 because the more distance I could put between my failure and my present,

90
00:07:20,000 --> 00:07:23,000
 the more God would like me.

91
00:07:23,000 --> 00:07:25,000
 Can you resonate with any of this?

92
00:07:25,000 --> 00:07:29,000
 Like, do you know what I'm talking about when I talk about shame?

93
00:07:29,000 --> 00:07:33,000
 What I'm really talking about is, you know what shame does?

94
00:07:33,000 --> 00:07:36,000
 Shame attacks your identity.

95
00:07:36,000 --> 00:07:45,000
 Like something happens where you move from "I failed" to "I'm a failure."

96
00:07:45,000 --> 00:07:47,000
 And so you might not lead with that.

97
00:07:47,000 --> 00:07:50,000
 If you're out at lunch and someone's like, "Hey, tell me about yourself.

98
00:07:50,000 --> 00:07:57,000
 Let me start out. I'm a failure. I like college football. How about you?"

99
00:07:57,000 --> 00:08:00,000
 Like, maybe you don't lead with it.

100
00:08:00,000 --> 00:08:04,000
 Maybe that's not even what you think on a regular basis.

101
00:08:04,000 --> 00:08:08,000
 But if you were to just kind of zoom out and look at your behavior,

102
00:08:08,000 --> 00:08:11,000
 you operate as a failure.

103
00:08:11,000 --> 00:08:16,000
 Like, it's in your wiring. It's your mentality.

104
00:08:16,000 --> 00:08:19,000
 It's the difference between your identity and activity.

105
00:08:19,000 --> 00:08:24,000
 I did fail. That's my activity. I did fail.

106
00:08:24,000 --> 00:08:29,000
 And yet my activity became my identity.

107
00:08:29,000 --> 00:08:32,000
 And what I had done became who I was.

108
00:08:32,000 --> 00:08:34,000
 I was a failure.

109
00:08:34,000 --> 00:08:38,000
 And so I just wonder how many people here, like if you were honest,

110
00:08:38,000 --> 00:08:42,000
 if you were to somehow just in the quietness of your own heart,

111
00:08:42,000 --> 00:08:45,000
 or when you're laying in bed at night and you finally turn the phone off

112
00:08:45,000 --> 00:08:48,000
 and all you are left with is your thoughts,

113
00:08:48,000 --> 00:08:53,000
 I wonder how many people just live under the crushing weight

114
00:08:53,000 --> 00:08:56,000
 of the banner over your life that you have put there.

115
00:08:56,000 --> 00:09:00,000
 And that banner reads "failure."

116
00:09:00,000 --> 00:09:04,000
 You know what's interesting is I talked to Sterling and Natalie

117
00:09:04,000 --> 00:09:07,000
 about that messed up air conditioning unit.

118
00:09:07,000 --> 00:09:09,000
 You know what they told me?

119
00:09:09,000 --> 00:09:13,000
 They said, "You know, before we understood what was going on,

120
00:09:13,000 --> 00:09:18,000
 we tried a bunch of different things to help Natalie with her health."

121
00:09:18,000 --> 00:09:21,000
 And so she would try different things,

122
00:09:21,000 --> 00:09:24,000
 and certain things would work for a short period of time.

123
00:09:24,000 --> 00:09:27,000
 So she might have a good day here or a good day here,

124
00:09:27,000 --> 00:09:30,000
 but ultimately her health would tank.

125
00:09:30,000 --> 00:09:34,000
 And it's because they weren't treating the problem.

126
00:09:34,000 --> 00:09:40,000
 So ultimately what they had to do was they had to identify the source of the problem,

127
00:09:40,000 --> 00:09:45,000
 and someone had to come in and rip out that busted system

128
00:09:45,000 --> 00:09:47,000
 and put in something new.

129
00:09:47,000 --> 00:09:49,000
 I tell you that just to say, you know what,

130
00:09:49,000 --> 00:09:52,000
 we have all sorts of ways of dealing with our shame.

131
00:09:52,000 --> 00:09:54,000
 All sorts of ways.

132
00:09:54,000 --> 00:09:56,000
 Like if you know what it feels like to fail,

133
00:09:56,000 --> 00:09:59,000
 you're like, "Man, if I could just have a do-over."

134
00:09:59,000 --> 00:10:02,000
 If you can look back and you can pinpoint something,

135
00:10:02,000 --> 00:10:06,000
 I wonder what you've done to kind of manage that shame.

136
00:10:06,000 --> 00:10:09,000
 Some of us, we make promises to God.

137
00:10:09,000 --> 00:10:11,000
 "God, I'm never going to look at porn again.

138
00:10:11,000 --> 00:10:15,000
 Mark the calendar, mark the day, this is it, never looking at porn again.

139
00:10:15,000 --> 00:10:19,000
 God, if you will just give me another girlfriend or another boyfriend,

140
00:10:19,000 --> 00:10:22,000
 I promise you I will never do anything bad again.

141
00:10:22,000 --> 00:10:24,000
 I will never do anything impure again.

142
00:10:24,000 --> 00:10:28,000
 I promise I am never going to do this again or that again."

143
00:10:28,000 --> 00:10:31,000
 We just make promises

144
00:10:31,000 --> 00:10:33,000
 because we think that if we can perform for God,

145
00:10:33,000 --> 00:10:35,000
 He will provide for us.

146
00:10:35,000 --> 00:10:39,000
 That's actually karma, do good, get good.

147
00:10:39,000 --> 00:10:43,000
 Or we don't make promises, we just compare.

148
00:10:43,000 --> 00:10:47,000
 Like we go out and we look for someone who has failed worse than we have,

149
00:10:47,000 --> 00:10:49,000
 and they just make us feel better about ourselves.

150
00:10:49,000 --> 00:10:54,000
 It's like, "I know I failed, but I didn't fail like that.

151
00:10:54,000 --> 00:10:58,000
 Like at least it wasn't that bad."

152
00:10:58,000 --> 00:11:00,000
 Or you know what we do is we punish ourselves.

153
00:11:00,000 --> 00:11:04,000
 Like we deprive ourselves of good gifts from God

154
00:11:04,000 --> 00:11:09,000
 because we think that if we can kind of pay for our failures,

155
00:11:09,000 --> 00:11:14,000
 like we can balance the scales in our own lives.

156
00:11:14,000 --> 00:11:17,000
 The reality is just like Sterling and Natalie needed someone to step in

157
00:11:17,000 --> 00:11:22,000
 and intervene and rip out the broken and busted air conditioning of their house,

158
00:11:22,000 --> 00:11:25,000
 Jesus Christ wants to step into our lives tonight

159
00:11:25,000 --> 00:11:31,000
 and rip out the busted failure

160
00:11:31,000 --> 00:11:37,000
 that is blowing shame and regret through the house of your soul,

161
00:11:37,000 --> 00:11:44,000
 poisoning your life and distorting your identity.

162
00:11:44,000 --> 00:11:49,000
 Jesus is going to show us what he wants to do with our past failure

163
00:11:49,000 --> 00:11:54,000
 by allowing us to see what he did with Peter's past failure.

164
00:11:54,000 --> 00:11:57,000
 And so if you have a Bible, I want you to turn with me tonight

165
00:11:57,000 --> 00:12:00,000
 all the way to the end of the book of John.

166
00:12:00,000 --> 00:12:02,000
 John chapter 21.

167
00:12:02,000 --> 00:12:05,000
 If you've been with us over the last several weeks,

168
00:12:05,000 --> 00:12:08,000
 we've been in this series called Glory.

169
00:12:08,000 --> 00:12:12,000
 The glory of God is the supreme goodness of God.

170
00:12:12,000 --> 00:12:15,000
 It is everything praiseworthy and good about God.

171
00:12:15,000 --> 00:12:21,000
 And God's glory, his goodness, has been demonstrated and displayed to us

172
00:12:21,000 --> 00:12:23,000
 in the person of Jesus Christ.

173
00:12:23,000 --> 00:12:26,000
 And so every week that we've been in the book of John,

174
00:12:26,000 --> 00:12:32,000
 we've just been looking at one activity of Jesus that displays the glory of God.

175
00:12:32,000 --> 00:12:38,000
 And today we're going to see Jesus as Restorer.

176
00:12:38,000 --> 00:12:45,000
 Jesus Christ is the Restorer of our souls.

177
00:12:45,000 --> 00:12:51,000
 If you're new to the Bible and you're not very familiar with Peter,

178
00:12:51,000 --> 00:12:56,000
 Peter was one of Jesus' 12 closest friends, but it was even more than that.

179
00:12:56,000 --> 00:13:01,000
 Like Jesus had three that he spent even more time with.

180
00:13:01,000 --> 00:13:03,000
 Peter was one of those.

181
00:13:03,000 --> 00:13:05,000
 Like he was super tight with Jesus.

182
00:13:05,000 --> 00:13:07,000
 Jesus gave Peter a new name.

183
00:13:07,000 --> 00:13:11,000
 Peter's original name was Simon, and Jesus gave him the name Peter.

184
00:13:11,000 --> 00:13:15,000
 Like when you give someone a nickname, that means you're tight with them.

185
00:13:15,000 --> 00:13:17,000
 That was Peter.

186
00:13:17,000 --> 00:13:20,000
 But if you're familiar with the Bible, then you know what Peter's greatest failure was.

187
00:13:20,000 --> 00:13:24,000
 What was it?

188
00:13:24,000 --> 00:13:27,000
 Yeah, he denied Jesus three times.

189
00:13:27,000 --> 00:13:31,000
 On the night that Jesus was betrayed and arrested.

190
00:13:31,000 --> 00:13:35,000
 So listen to the wording before we get to John 21.

191
00:13:35,000 --> 00:13:42,000
 Listen to the wording of Luke 22, which tells us what happens right after Peter denies Jesus for the third time.

192
00:13:42,000 --> 00:13:45,000
 It says this in Luke 22, verse 61.

193
00:13:45,000 --> 00:13:50,000
 It says, "And the Lord turned and looked at Peter, and Peter remembered the saying of the Lord,

194
00:13:50,000 --> 00:13:55,000
 how he had said to him, 'Before the rooster crows today, you will deny me three times.'

195
00:13:55,000 --> 00:13:59,000
 And he went out and wept bitterly."

196
00:13:59,000 --> 00:14:01,000
 Like this is in the Bible.

197
00:14:01,000 --> 00:14:03,000
 Like I don't know what you think is in the Bible.

198
00:14:03,000 --> 00:14:13,000
 If you've never taken time to read it, this is not just some like mythical world of larger than life people who never struggle.

199
00:14:13,000 --> 00:14:15,000
 It's the opposite.

200
00:14:15,000 --> 00:14:19,000
 It is real down to earth people who have real problems.

201
00:14:19,000 --> 00:14:26,000
 And one of Jesus' closest friends denied him three times after he said he wouldn't.

202
00:14:26,000 --> 00:14:28,000
 And so what was the result?

203
00:14:28,000 --> 00:14:30,000
 He actually locks eyes with Jesus.

204
00:14:30,000 --> 00:14:35,000
 And in that moment, he sees a sin for what it is, and he goes out and he weeps bitterly.

205
00:14:35,000 --> 00:14:36,000
 Now think about it.

206
00:14:36,000 --> 00:14:47,000
 If you're God, and one of your closest friends just betrays you, you've got options.

207
00:14:47,000 --> 00:14:48,000
 Right?

208
00:14:48,000 --> 00:14:50,000
 Like you're in charge of that guy's story.

209
00:14:50,000 --> 00:14:56,000
 That guy's story could be like, "And Peter was never heard from again."

210
00:14:56,000 --> 00:15:05,000
 Or like, "The ground split open and swallowed Peter whole, and he was never heard from again."

211
00:15:05,000 --> 00:15:09,000
 Like, there's options.

212
00:15:09,000 --> 00:15:19,000
 And yet we turn to John chapter 21, and it says this, verse 1.

213
00:15:19,000 --> 00:15:20,000
 It says, "After this."

214
00:15:20,000 --> 00:15:22,000
 After what?

215
00:15:22,000 --> 00:15:25,000
 After Jesus went to the cross.

216
00:15:25,000 --> 00:15:27,000
 After Jesus bore our sin and shame.

217
00:15:27,000 --> 00:15:33,000
 After Jesus on the third day walked out of the tomb victoriously, conquering Satan, sin, and death.

218
00:15:33,000 --> 00:15:35,000
 After that.

219
00:15:35,000 --> 00:15:38,000
 After this, Jesus revealed himself.

220
00:15:38,000 --> 00:15:41,000
 What's the next word?

221
00:15:41,000 --> 00:15:42,000
 This isn't a trick.

222
00:15:42,000 --> 00:15:44,000
 Like, what's the next word?

223
00:15:44,000 --> 00:15:45,000
 Again.

224
00:15:45,000 --> 00:15:47,000
 You're like, "You want to highlight that word?"

225
00:15:47,000 --> 00:15:49,000
 Yes.

226
00:15:49,000 --> 00:15:57,000
 He reveals himself again to the disciples, which included Peter, by the Sea of Tiberias.

227
00:15:57,000 --> 00:16:00,000
 And he revealed himself in this way.

228
00:16:00,000 --> 00:16:02,000
 Here's why I highlight again.

229
00:16:02,000 --> 00:16:06,000
 Like, Jesus could have done anything he wanted with Peter.

230
00:16:06,000 --> 00:16:17,000
 And yet he reveals himself to Peter, not just once, not just twice, but in John 21, this is him revealing himself again.

231
00:16:17,000 --> 00:16:22,000
 Because it's the third time that he has shown up in Peter's life.

232
00:16:22,000 --> 00:16:29,000
 You know what's interesting is when we think about Jesus being betrayed and arrested, we only think about Judas and Peter.

233
00:16:29,000 --> 00:16:34,000
 Judas is the guy who betrayed Jesus, and Peter is the guy who denied Jesus.

234
00:16:34,000 --> 00:16:39,000
 But have you ever read the verse, Matthew 26, 56, which says this about the rest of the disciples?

235
00:16:39,000 --> 00:16:45,000
 It says, "Then all the disciples left him and fled."

236
